8. In this exercise, we will generate simulated data, and will then use this data to perform best subset selection.

  1. Use the rnorm() function to generate a predictor \(X\) of length \(n\) = 100, as well as a noise vector \(\epsilon\) of length \(n\) = 100.
set.seed(37)
x <- rnorm(100)
eps <- rnorm(100)
  1. Generate a response vector Y of length n = 100 according to the model \(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1X + \beta_2X^2 + \beta_3X^3 +\epsilon\), where \(\beta_0, \beta_1, \beta_2,\beta_3\) are constants of your choice.
b0 <- 1
b1 <- 9

b3 <- 8
y <- b0 + b1*x + b2*x^2 + b3*x^3 + eps
  1. Use the \(regsubsets()\) function to perform best subset selection in order to choose the best model containing the predictors \(X,X^2,...,X^{10}\). What is the best model obtained according to Cp, BIC, and adjusted R2? Show some plots to provide evidence for your answer, and report the coefficients of the best model obtained. Note you will need to use the \(data.frame()\) function to create a single data set containing both \(X\) and \(Y\) ..

10. We have seen that as the number of features used in a model increases, the training error will necessarily decrease, but the test error may not. We will now explore this in a simulated data set.

  1. Generate a data set with p = 20 features, n = 1,000 observations, and an associated quantitative response vector generated according to the model \(Y = X\beta +\epsilon\), where \(\beta\) has some elements that are exactly equal to zero.

b <- rnorm(20)
zeroElem <- sample(20,0.2*20)
b[zeroElem] <- 0
b <- as.matrix(b)

X <- data.frame(replicate(20,rnorm(1000)))
X <- as.matrix(X)

eps <- as.matrix(rnorm(1000))
Y <- X %*% b + eps

# best = 16
#?colnames
errors <- rep(0, 20)
xCols <-  colnames(X, do.NULL = FALSE, prefix = "col")
for (i in 1:20) {
    bestCoef <- coef(fit.best, id = i)
    errors[i] <- sqrt(sum((b[xCols %in% names(bestCoef)] - bestCoef[names(bestCoef) %in% xCols])^2) + sum(b[!(xCols %in% names(bestCoef))])^2)
}
errorMin <- which.min(errors)
plot(errors, xlab = "number of varibles", ylab = "MSE", pch = 19, col="cyan3", type = "l")
points(errorMin, errors[errorMin], col="purple", cex=2, pch=20)

train <- sample(nrow(boston), 0.7*nrow(boston))
boston.train <- boston[train, ]
boston.test <- boston[-train, ]

X.train <- model.matrix(crim~., data = boston.train)
y.train <- boston.train$crim
X.test <- model.matrix(crim~., data = boston.test)

### best subset
best.mod <- regsubsets(crim~., data = boston.train, nvmax = 20)
best.summary <- summary(best.mod)
#find a best model
minBIC <- which.min(best.summary$bic)  #2
minCP <- which.min(best.summary$cp)   
maxADJR2 <- which.max(best.summary$adjr2) 

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
#BIC
plot(best.summary$bic, xlab = "flexibility", ylab = "BIC", col="orange", type = "l")
points(minBIC,best.summary$bic[minBIC], col="skyblue", cex=2, pch = 20)
#C_p
plot(best.summary$cp, xlab = "flexibility", ylab = "C_p", col="orange", type = "l")
points(minCP,best.summary$cp[minCP], col="skyblue", cex=2, pch = 20)
#adjusted R^2
plot(best.summary$adjr2, xlab = "flexibility", ylab = "adjusted R^2", col="orange",type = "l")
points(maxADJR2,best.summary$adjr2[maxADJR2], col="skyblue", cex=2, pch = 20)
#validation error
Xtest <-  X.test #354*13
error <- c()
for (i in 1:12) {
  bestCoef <- as.matrix(coef(best.mod, id = i)) 
  yHat <- Xtest[, colnames(Xtest) %in% names(coef(best.mod, id = i))] %*% bestCoef   
  error[i] <- mean( abs(boston.test$crim[i] - yHat[i]) )
}

minError <- which.min(error) #3 0.01678737
plot(error, xlab = "number of Variables", ylab = "validation mean error", type = "l", col="orange")
points(minError, error[minError], col="skyblue", cex = 2, pch=20)
